Phoenix-RTOS: libXfont2 fonts.dir/fonts.alias open uses fdopen(fd, "rt").

libphoenix's stdio mode parser (sources/libphoenix/stdio/file.c string2mode())
does NOT accept the glibc "t" (text) mode flag: for a mode of "rt" it takes the
'r' branch, sees 't' (not 'b'/'\0'/'+'/'c') and returns -1, so fdopen() sets
EINVAL and returns NULL. dirfile.c then treats the NULL FILE* as a failed open
with errno != ENOENT and returns BadFontPath from FontFileReadDirectory().

Consequence (task #56): FontFileInitFPE() fails for every disk font directory,
so dix SetFontPathElements() silently drops the disk FPE (the "Could not init
font path element" message is DebugF, a no-op without -DDEBUG) and the running
server font path collapses to "built-ins" only. No named disk font
(8x13/9x15/10x20/-misc-fixed-*) can load, regardless of gzip/PCF content — which
is exactly why uncompressing the fonts never helped. Observed on HW via
xfontprobe: XGetFontPath -> 1 element "built-ins"; disk=0/3.

Fix: drop the non-portable "t" — POSIX fopen/fdopen ignore 't' and "r" is
text-mode by default on POSIX, so "r" is equivalent everywhere AND accepted by
libphoenix. (The "%[^\n]\n"/"%d\n" fscanf reads on these streams are handled
conformantly by libphoenix's scanf, so this is a complete fix, not a half-fix.)

A more general fix (make libphoenix string2mode() ignore a 't' flag) is tracked
as a follow-up; it is a --scope core change with a wider blast radius, so the
localized X-side patch is used to unblock #56.

--- a/src/fontfile/dirfile.c
+++ b/src/fontfile/dirfile.c
@@ -98,7 +98,7 @@ FontFileReadDirectory (const char *directory, FontDirectoryPtr *pdir)
 #ifndef WIN32
     file_fd = open(dir_file, O_RDONLY | O_NOFOLLOW);
     if (file_fd >= 0) {
-	file = fdopen(file_fd, "rt");
+	file = fdopen(file_fd, "r");
     }
 #else
     file = fopen(dir_file, "rt");
@@ -295,7 +295,7 @@ ReadFontAlias(char *directory, Bool isFile, FontDirectoryPtr *pdir)
 #ifndef WIN32
     file_fd = open(alias_file, O_RDONLY | O_NOFOLLOW);
     if (file_fd >= 0) {
-	file = fdopen(file_fd, "rt");
+	file = fdopen(file_fd, "r");
     }
 #else
     file = fopen(alias_file, "rt");
